4.5 Quality Assurance Methods Used 
 
To ensure the Sethro Medical Center management system is reliable, secure, and user-friendly, the 
following quality assurance (QA) techniques were implemented during the development process. 
 
1. Frontend Validation 
 
• Comprehensive input validation was implemented across all user registration and data entry forms 
  using React Hook Form and Zod. 
• Critical fields such as patient email addresses, secure passwords, phone numbers, and appointment 
  dates are validated on the client-side before submission. 
• The system prevents common errors such as blank required inputs, invalid email formats, and 
  incorrect data types, providing immediate feedback to the user. 
 
2. Backend and API Validation 
 
• Secure backend validation is performed within Next.js Server Actions and API routes using Zod 
  schemas to ensure that incoming data meets strict criteria. 
• Data integrity is maintained by checking: 
  - Data types and formats (e.g., ensuring numeric price fields and valid string structures). 
  - Required fields for clinical records, such as prescription items and patient IDs. 
  - Business rules, such as ensuring appointment slots are within valid timeframes and pharmacy 
    stock levels are non-negative. 
 
3. Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) & Security 
 
• A robust middleware layer was implemented to verify user identity and roles (Admin, Doctor, 
  Pharmacist, etc.) for every protected request using JSON Web Tokens (JWT). 
• Access control ensures that sensitive medical data and administrative settings are only accessible 
  by authorized personnel. 
• Unauthorized access attempts are automatically detected and redirected to a secure login or 
  unauthorized access page. 
 
4. Error Handling and Logging 
 
• The system implements structured error handling to catch and manage database failures or 
  invalid user requests gracefully. 
• Meaningful error messages are presented to users, while detailed technical logs are recorded 
  using Winston for developer-side monitoring and debugging. 
• This dual approach ensures a smooth user experience while providing necessary information for 
  maintaining system stability. 
 
5. Manual Testing and User Flow Verification 
 
• The system underwent extensive manual testing to verify business logic and user journeys for 
  every hospital persona: 
  - Patient registration and appointment booking flows. 
  - Medical history updates and prescription generation by doctors. 
  - Pharmacy inventory management and bill settlement processes. 
• Edge cases, such as expired session tokens and conflicting appointment slots, were tested 
  to ensure correct system behavior under unexpected conditions. 
 
6. Browser and Device Compatibility 
 
• The interface was tested on modern web browsers including Google Chrome, Mozilla Firefox, 
  and Microsoft Edge. 
• Responsive design testing was conducted to ensure the application remains fully functional 
  and visually consistent on desktops, tablets, and smartphones.
